{"id":14881306,"mediaExerciseId":"59d11e24-e344-4165-86d3-eb0e3d03102b","exerciseName":"11","chapterName":"11","chapterTitle":"Project Analysis and Evaluation","groupId":612352,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":377,"solutions":[{"id":6092529,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise,  we will determine the percentage change in operating cash flow.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The degree of operating leverage reflects the susceptibility of the company's profit to the changes in the number of units sold. This can be solved using these formulas:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{DOL}&=\\dfrac{\\Delta \\text{OCF}}{\\Delta \\text{Q}}\\\\[15pt]\n&=1+\\dfrac{\\text{FC}}{\\text{OCF}}\n\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"We first need to solve for $\\Delta Q$ by taking the percentage change.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\Delta Q&=\\dfrac{48,000-45,000}{45,000}\\\\[15pt]\n&=0.0667\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Since we already have the value for the change in Q, we can rewrite the first formula to solve for the change in OCF:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\Delta OCF&=DOL \\times \\Delta Q\\\\\n&=2.79 \\times0.0667\\\\\n&=0.186\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nThe percentage change in cashflow is $0.186$ or $18.6\\%$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Now that we have the value for change in OCF, we can now check how it affects the DOL. In this case, we will now use the second formula for DOL:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{DOL}&=1+\\dfrac{\\text{FC}}{\\text{OCF}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nSince OCF is at the denominator, this means that an increase in OCF will result in a decrease in the DOL, and vice versa. Therefore, we can conclude that the DOL will decrease in this scenario. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"0b58b2ba-946e-439c-9da7-fbfc841f84d9","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881307,"exerciseName":"12","page":377,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8a446c6a-fd02-42a4-ba9c-02de91df6dad","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-11-questions-and-problems-12-8a446c6a-fd02-42a4-ba9c-02de91df6dad"},{"id":14881308,"exerciseName":"13","page":377,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"9939cee8-3582-47e8-8706-dcdb0087ec9a","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-11-questions-and-problems-13-9939cee8-3582-47e8-8706-dcdb0087ec9a"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881305,"exerciseName":"10","page":377,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"05b26ead-d44d-455c-9586-5266d620f78b","_webUrl":"ht